hands_on_practices.problem:
A hypothetical diatomic molecule, denoted as XY, is studied in a gas-phase spectroscopy experiment. It is observed that upon irradiation with ultraviolet light, the molecule undergoes dissociation into its constituent atomic fragments, X and Y. Subsequent analysis of the atomic emission spectra from the fragments reveals that atom X is produced in an electronic state with a spin multiplicity of 2 (a doublet state), and atom Y is produced in an electronic state with a spin multiplicity of 3 (a triplet state).

The conservation of total spin angular momentum is a fundamental principle in such molecular processes, as described by the Wigner-Witmer correlation rules. These rules connect the electronic states of the separated atoms to the possible electronic states of the parent molecule. Based on this principle, determine the set of all possible spin multiplicities for the parent molecular state XY from which this dissociation can occur.

Which of the following options represents the correct and complete set of possible spin multiplicities for the parent molecule XY?

A) {1, 3}

B) {2, 4}

C) {1, 2, 3}

D) {3, 5}

E) {2, 3, 4}
